Boil a full #kettle{}.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks (peel first if you prefer).

Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

Add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a #knife{} through, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken thigh{260%grams} to the pan and season with @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch}.

Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the chicken has browned, add the garlic and @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder). Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @chicken stock paste{10%grams} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} for the sauce (see pantry for amount). Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer.

Cook until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce has thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the sauce has thickened and the chicken is cooked, stir through the @double cream{75%grams} and @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%grams}.

Season with salt and pepper.

Add the @baby spinach{40%grams} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Meanwhile, once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{knob} and a splash of @?milk{splash} and mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}.

Season with salt and pepper.

When everything's ready, spoon the creamy tomato Cajun chicken into your #bowls{}.

Serve the mash alongside. Enjoy!